{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nThe plan-v2 impact model floors four failure-mode axes at 0.85 (above every blocking threshold) whenever the axis is non-none at ANY grade - the floor is grade-blind. Calibration 3 (task relishable-ammonitic-hoverfly; evidence comment on this story, 2026-07-15) measured the consequence on the plan-v2 segment: 35.5% of ALL blocking findings (807/2271) are floor-driven (would not block without the override), ac_unverifiable alone is 48.9% of the floor-driven set, 52/100 of a classified sample fired at grade=low, and the oracle-kind classification split 56% underspecified_oracle / 37% broken-oracle-shaped / 7% missing_oracle. The dominant floor-driven class is \"a check exists, the plan just doesn't spell out the exact command/file/value\" - a refinement demand that today auto-blocks with the same force as a genuinely untestable criterion. This story splits the axis so severity follows the actual defect.\n\n## What\nReplace the binary-ish ac_unverifiable severity grading with a THREE-value oracle-kind grade in the plan-review verification model, assigned explicitly by the pass-2 verifier (the calibration-3 evidence motivates three, not two - a broken oracle is not a refinement):\n- missing_oracle: no verification method exists or could exist as the criterion is phrased (7% of sample) - KEEPS the 0.85 hard floor.\n- broken_oracle: a stated proving command/symbol/count is factually wrong - nonexistent path, wrong CLI, contradictory assertion - so the stated verification CANNOT pass (37% of sample) - KEEPS the 0.85 hard floor (the check is protective; these are real plan defects).\n- underspecified_oracle: a check exists or is clearly constructible; the finding demands the exact command/file/expected value (56% of sample) - scores BELOW the lowest blocking threshold in force after calibration 3 (0.60), i.e. maps to an impact contribution <= 0.55, so it surfaces and is coached but never auto-blocks.\nBOTH verifier prompts define the three grades with one worked example each drawn from the calibration-3 classified sample (the gate YAML routes to TWO prompt files: src/rebar/llm/reviewers/plan_review_verifier.md AND plan_review_verifier_agentic.md - both change in lockstep). SCORING MECHANICS (exact decide.py change): impact_plan currently scores all seven axes through the shared ordinal map _SEV01 ({none,low,medium,high}) in TWO generic loops - the contribs list comprehension over _PLAN_SEVERITY_AXES and the has_override any() over _PLAN_HARD_OVERRIDE_AXES. ac_unverifiable is REMOVED from both generic loops and special-cased: (1) contribs = [_SEV01.get(attrs.get(a), 0.0) for a in _PLAN_SEVERITY_AXES if a != \"ac_unverifiable\"] + [ORACLE_GRADE01.get(attrs.get(\"ac_unverifiable\"), 0.0)]; (2) has_override = any(_SEV01.get(attrs.get(a), 0.0) > 0.0 for a in _PLAN_HARD_OVERRIDE_AXES if a != \"ac_unverifiable\") or attrs.get(\"ac_unverifiable\") in (\"broken_oracle\", \"missing_oracle\"). ORACLE_GRADE01 = {\"none\": 0.0, \"underspecified_oracle\": UNDERSPECIFIED_ORACLE_CONTRIB, \"broken_oracle\": 1.0, \"missing_oracle\": 1.0} with UNDERSPECIFIED_ORACLE_CONTRIB = 0.55 defined as a named module constant whose comment states its invariant (strictly below the lowest blocking threshold in criteria_routing.json), and a unit test asserts UNDERSPECIFIED_ORACLE_CONTRIB < min(block_threshold over blocking-posture criteria) so a future threshold recalibration below 0.55 fails loudly instead of silently re-enabling blocks. An unknown/legacy grade string maps to 0.0 via .get() default in plan-v3 scoring - legacy records are never scored with plan-v3 code anyway (segmentation, below). The other six axes keep _SEV01 and the any-non-none override unchanged. WRITE-TIME ENFORCEMENT (the concrete mechanism): src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/verify.py owns PlanSeverityAttrs; its ac_unverifiable field changes from the ordinal type to Literal[\"none\", \"underspecified_oracle\", \"broken_oracle\", \"missing_oracle\"], so Pydantic strict validation rejects out-of-vocabulary grades at verification-parse time - that field is the closed-set gate the ACs pin. OPERATOR-ATTESTED ENRICH: workflow_ops.enrich_operator_attested's guard changes from `not in (None, \"\", \"none\")` to the explicit clearable set `in (\"missing_oracle\", \"underspecified_oracle\")` (clears to \"none\" when attested evidence satisfies the criterion - the recorded attestation IS the oracle) while broken_oracle is never cleared (a factually wrong stated command is not cured by an attestation) - this file is in Scope and the asymmetry is pinned by test. BACK-COMPAT: the closed-set validation applies to NEW plan-v3 verifications at parse time; already-stored plan-v2 sidecars keep their legacy {low,medium,high} grades and are read as-is - every calibration/replay consumer segments by impact_model_version (ADR 0036), so old records are never scored with new semantics - and this is pinned by a TEST (a plan-v2 fixture sidecar with grade \"low\" round-trips unmodified through latest_review_result/all_review_results). The sidecar SCHEMA id stays plan_review_result_v2: the payload shape (keys, nesting) is unchanged - only the value vocabulary of one severity-attribute field changes - so the schema-string guard in the readers keeps matching; IMPACT_MODEL_VERSION (plan-v3) is the segmentation key for the semantics change. ROLLBACK: the version bump makes back-out clean - reverting the change restores plan-v2 semantics and the corpora stay segmented; no expand-contract migration is needed because sidecars are immutable records, not migrated state. IMPACT_MODEL_VERSION bumps plan-v2 -> plan-v3 in the same change. The other three override axes (dod_uncertifiable, undecomposed, divergent_implementation) keep their ordinal vocabulary and any-non-none floor, untouched in this story (their grade mix is unmeasured; calibration 4 scope).\n\n## Scope\n- src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/decide.py: ORACLE_GRADE01 + UNDERSPECIFIED_ORACLE_CONTRIB constants; ac_unverifiable excluded from both generic _SEV01 loops and special-cased per the exact change spec above.\n- src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/verify.py: PlanSeverityAttrs.ac_unverifiable becomes the closed Literal grade type (the write-time enforcement mechanism).\n- src/rebar/llm/plan_review/workflow_ops.py: enrich_operator_attested vocabulary update (clears missing/underspecified on attestation, never broken_oracle).\n- src/rebar/llm/reviewers/plan_review_verifier.md AND plan_review_verifier_agentic.md: three-grade definitions + one worked example each; the plan-review verification output schema accepts exactly {none, underspecified_oracle, broken_oracle, missing_oracle} for the axis and rejects anything else at write time.\n- src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py: IMPACT_MODEL_VERSION bump to plan-v3; the grade persists in verification.severity_attributes as today (values change, key stays).\n- Unit tests: tests/unit/test_impact_plan.py (replace old low/medium/high ac_unverifiable pins with the three-grade pins; keep other-axis pins), tests/unit/test_impact_model_versioning.py (plan-v2 -> plan-v3 assertion), tests/unit/_audit_page_helpers.py (hardcoded plan-v2 string updated), new pins for: schema acceptance AND rejection of an invalid grade, sidecar persistence, the enrich asymmetry, the UNDERSPECIFIED_ORACLE_CONTRIB < min(blocking thresholds) invariant, and the plan-v2 legacy-fixture read-as-is round-trip.\n- docs/plan-review-gate.md: the floor description updated to the graded rule with the back-compat note.\n- Coordination: story ea39 (R5 kernel sub-answer, epic pastoral-aquatic-viper) also plans a version bump and depends_on this story - if both land close together the bumps compose (v3 then v4), never merge into one ambiguous version.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The verification model accepts exactly the closed grade set {none, underspecified_oracle, broken_oracle, missing_oracle} for ac_unverifiable on new plan-v3 verifications - pinned by BOTH an acceptance test and a rejection test for an out-of-vocabulary grade - and both verifier prompts (single-turn + agentic) define each grade with one worked example.\n- [ ] Impact scoring pinned by unit tests: missing_oracle and broken_oracle findings floor at >= 0.85; underspecified_oracle findings score <= 0.55 (below the 0.60 lowest blocking threshold) and never trigger the hard floor; the other three override axes floor unchanged.\n- [ ] IMPACT_MODEL_VERSION is plan-v3 in the same change (test_impact_model_versioning.py updated), the grade persists per finding in the REVIEW_RESULT sidecar (pinned by test), legacy plan-v2 records are read as-is (segmentation by version is the back-compat mechanism, asserted in the doc note), and enrich_operator_attested clears missing/underspecified but never broken_oracle (pinned by test).\n- [ ] docs/plan-review-gate.md documents the three-grade rule citing the calibration-3 evidence comment on this story, and the change is MERGED through Gerrit (LLM-Review +1, Verified +1)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784149441166332001,"uuid":"dd2338fd-2384-49ee-99e0-cfa0449fec0d"}